The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Oct. 26: A retiring secretary from the human resource development ministry has applied for a vice-chancellors post, a job that will require him to depend on juniors in the ministry.           
	Outgoing higher education secretary R.P. Agrawal applied for the post at the National University of Educational Planning and Administration. A selection panel has approved his candidature in principle. HRD minister Kapil Sibal and the President will also need to clear it. Agrawal retires on October 31.           
	The move is controversial as he applied while he was in a position to influence decisions as the countrys highest ranking bureaucrat in higher education.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): Actor Hrithik Roshan was warned not to play loud music in a late Sunday night party at his Juhu residence. Police reached his house around 2am after somebody rang them up to complain. The actor was celebrating his mother, Pinkys birthday. Hrithik told the police the party was winding up and the volume had already been reduced.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): Tabla maestro Zakir Hussains mother Bavi Begum Allah Rakha passed away on Saturday. The wife of tabla legend Allah Rakha was known as Ammaji in her family. She was 82.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Manmohan Singh has given his approval to the National Mission on Sustaining the Himalayan Eco-system and called for greater engagement among nations, including China and Pakistan, which share the mountain range. The approval is significant as India will be part of the climate change talks in Copenhagen in December to decide a successor to the Kyoto Protocol to check global warming.                  
	 Dubai (PTI): Several people were injured in a stampede after they tried to gatecrash the venue of a reality show featuring southern star Mammootty. Over 15,000 fans had gathered at the Dubai Airport Expo.
                                                                                                                           
